{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:11:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:11:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19682"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19682"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.17,0.37,0.09,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112264"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94313"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"507"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43728"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112264"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as an accountant. He reports smoking one pack of cigarettes per day for the past 35 years. He has no respiratory symptoms. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sputum cytology","Chest X-ray","No further investigation required","Spirometry testing","Referral for low-dose CT scan"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient meets the criteria for lung cancer screening, which commenced on the 1st of July 2025 in Australia. He is 58 years old (within the 50-70 year range), is asymptomatic, and has a 35 pack-year smoking history (1 pack per day \u00d7 35 years). Current smokers with this level of exposure should be offered screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for low-dose CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended screening test for lung cancer in high-risk individuals. Studies have shown that 2 yearly low-dose CT screening can reduce lung cancer mortality in this population. The National Cancer Screening Register (NCSR) will notify the patient of a reminder for repeat screening in 2 years time if the initial scan is reported as normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a screening test for lung cancer as it has not been shown to reduce mortality. It may miss small lesions that would be detected on CT scanning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpirometry testing\u003C/strong\u003E measures lung function and may be useful in assessing for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, but it is not a screening test for lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a screening test for lung cancer due to poor sensitivity and specificity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further investigation\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this patient meets established criteria for lung cancer screening. The consultation also presents an opportunity to provide smoking cessation advice and support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELung cancer screening eligibility criteria includes: aged between 50 and 70 years, being asymptomatic for lung cancer; and having a history of at least 30 pack-years of cigarette smoking and either still smoking or having quit within the past 10 years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lung cancer screening with low-dose CT is recommended for people aged 50-70 years with a 30 pack-year smoking history who currently smoke or quit within 10 years.","Pack-years are calculated by multiplying the number of packs smoked per day by the number of years smoked.","Asymptomatic patients who meet screening criteria should be referred for low-dose CT scanning."],"references":["How the NLCSP will work. Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. [cited 2025 Mar] Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/our-work/nlcsp/how-it-works"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94313"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94313"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-27T17:03:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-27T17:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112264"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}